<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n14030b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n14" href="#n14030b">N14 (VI.B.7)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n14all.htm#n14030b"> 30(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ capon</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">So also did this singer hold up to contumacy the materialism and immortality of the Roman hierarchy, who &ldquo;filled their Guelphish coffers&rdquo; with German gold and silver, in order that their &ldquo;priests might <mark>eat capons and quaff wine</mark>,&rdquo; while Germans &ldquo;prayed and fasted for them.&rdquo; The farce of Absolution came equally under the sting of his lash, von der Vogelweide solemnly asserting that God alone had the power to forgive sins, and that a Pope who dared to assume this right, without first having convinced himself of the sinner&apos;s penitence, deserved to be stoned as soon as ever he consigned one man to hell. <small> Ernst Boldt, <a name="BFLS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BFLS"><cite title="source">From Luther to Steiner</cite></a>, (1921) 4-5</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c05228f" href="c05all.htm#c05228f">VI.C.05:228(f)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
